1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,130
I worked with her to help her see joy and pleasure in her past, instead of total disappointment.

2
00:00:06,400 --> 00:00:09,569
After six months, she began to show improvement.

3
00:00:09,760 --> 00:00:13,010
At that point, I gave her a special assignment.

4
00:00:13,280 --> 00:00:19,970
Each day, I asked her to think of and write down three specific reasons she has to be happy.

5
00:00:20,160 --> 00:00:25,250
Then, at her next appointment with me, on Thursdays, I'd go over her list with her.

6
00:00:25,520 --> 00:00:28,530
I continued this sort of treatment for three months.

7
00:00:28,640 --> 00:00:31,250
Her improvement was very satisfactory.

8
00:00:31,360 --> 00:00:35,010
Today, that woman is very well adjusted to her situation.

9
00:00:35,200 --> 00:00:38,930
She's positive and certainly as happy as most people.

10
00:00:39,440 --> 00:00:45,490
When this woman quit drawing negatives from her memory bank, she was headed toward recovery.

11
00:00:45,920 --> 00:00:57,010
Whether the psychological problem is big or little, the cure comes when one learns to quit drawing negatives from one's memory bank and withdraws positives instead.

12
00:00:57,600 --> 00:00:59,809
Don't build mental monsters.

13
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:04,130
Refuse to withdraw the unpleasant thoughts from your memory bank.

14
00:01:04,400 --> 00:01:09,650
When you remember situations of any kind, concentrate on the good part of the experience.

15
00:01:09,760 --> 00:01:10,930
Forget the bad.

16
00:01:11,120 --> 00:01:11,970
Bury it.

17
00:01:12,240 --> 00:01:17,730
If you find yourself thinking about the negative side, turn your mind off completely.

18
00:01:18,240 --> 00:01:22,289
And here is something very significant and very encouraging.

19
00:01:22,640 --> 00:01:25,890
Your mind wants you to forget the unpleasant.

20
00:01:26,080 --> 00:01:34,289
If you will just cooperate, unpleasant memories will gradually shrivel and the teller in your memory bank will cancel them out.

21
00:01:34,960 --> 00:01:41,970
Dr. Melvin S. Hatwick, noted advertising psychologist, in commenting on our ability to remember,

22
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:48,130
says, When the feeling aroused is pleasant, the advertisement has a better chance to be remembered.

23
00:01:48,240 --> 00:01:54,690
When the feeling aroused is unpleasant, the reader or listener tends to forget the advertisement message.

24
00:01:54,880 --> 00:01:57,809
The unpleasant runs counter to what we want.

25
00:01:57,920 --> 00:01:59,730
We don't want to remember it.

26
00:02:00,160 --> 00:02:06,609
In brief, it really is easy to forget the unpleasant if we simply refuse to recall it.

27
00:02:06,960 --> 00:02:10,450
Withdraw only positive thoughts from your memory bank.

28
00:02:10,480 --> 00:02:17,730
Let the others fade away, and your confidence, that feeling of being on top of the world, will zoom upward.

29
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:25,809
You take a big step forward toward conquering fear when you refuse to remember negative, self-deprecating thoughts.

